        <h2>When & Where can you see it?</h2>
        <p>Cepheus is a northern constellation. It’s visible from about +90° down to roughly −1° latitude.</p>
        <p>If you’re in the mid-to-far northern hemisphere, it can be <strong>circumpolar</strong>. That means it never really sets, so you can look for it any clear night.</p>
        <p>It’s easiest in the evenings during fall. Around <strong>9 PM in November</strong>, Cepheus sits high in the sky and is much more obvious.</p>
