        <h2>Cool Features</h2>
        <p>Cepheus sits right on the Milky Way, so it’s packed with star fields and nebulae.</p>
        <p>A big highlight is the <strong>IC 1396</strong> region. It includes the <strong>Elephant’s Trunk Nebula</strong>, a tall pillar of gas and dust being shaped by nearby young stars.</p>
        <p>Another favorite is the <strong>Iris Nebula (NGC 7023)</strong>, a blue reflection nebula that really pops in long-exposure photos.</p>
        <p>If you’re using binoculars or a small telescope, <strong>NGC 188</strong> is a neat one to try. It’s an old open cluster close to the north celestial pole.</p>
        <p>And if you’re up for a challenge, the <strong>Fireworks Galaxy (NGC 6946)</strong> sits near the Cepheus/Cygnus border. It’s faint, but it’s famous for multiple observed supernovae.</p>
        <p>One more fun fact: Cepheus is home to <strong>Delta Cephei</strong>, the star that gave Cepheid variables their name. Cepheids are used to measure distances across the galaxy and beyond.</p>
